  <li>
    <h2 class="docs-header">triangle</h2>
    <p>Uses the <code>0 * 0</code> element with borders trick to draw arrows. The base styles for creating CSS triangles can be used with `%triangle` as placeholder or you can have it applied directly to your triangle element.</p>
<pre class="mixin"><code class="mixin-name">@mixin triangle-base()</code></pre>
<pre class="mixin"><code class="mixin-name">@mixin triangle( $size, $color, $direction, $base )</code><code class="mixin-desc">@param $size
  @type unit (pixel, em, rem)
@param $color
  @type color
@param $direction
  @type string ('up', 'right', 'down', 'left', 'up-right', 'up-left', 'down-right', 'down-left')
  @desc The direction that the triangle will point.
@param $base
  @type boolean (true, false)
  @default false
  @desc whether or not triangle base styles are applied individually or extended to the placeholder `%triangle`</code></pre>
    <h3 class="docs-header">Example Usage</h3>
<pre><code>// SCSS
%triangle {
  @include triangle-base;
}
.example-triangle-1 {
  @include triangle( 14px, $blue, 'left' );
}
.example-triangle-2 {
  @include triangle( 14px, $violet, 'down' );
}
.example-triangle-3 {
  @include triangle( 14px, $red, 'right' );
}

// CSS
.example-triangle-1,
.example-triangle-2,
.example-triangle-3 {
  content: "";
  display: inline-block;
  width: 0;
  height: 0;
  border: 0 none;
  border-style: solid;
  border-color: transparent;
}
.example-triangle-1 {
  border-width: 14px 14px 14px 0;
  border-right-color: #2ab0ea;
}
.example-triangle-2 {
  border-width: 14px 14px 0 14px;
  border-top-color: #bc6bd3;
}
.example-triangle-3 {
  border-width: 14px 0 14px 14px;
  border-left-color: #de5151;
}
</code></pre>
